['Broke mindsets trade time for money

Momentum‚Ä¶ https://t.co/8wjLpdaWOm", 'If you want to make millions as an entrepreneur, I‚Äôve done it twice with two businesses in two different industries.

I also made a lot of mistakes along the way.

So here are 10 pieces of advice I‚Äôd give myself if I had to do it again:', 'My first business put me $180,000 in debt because I ignored my instinct.

If you've felt it, you know what I mean", 'It would have been easy for me to play the victim

Immigrant parents, coming to the US with nothing

I could have said "woe is me", never amounted to anything, and no one would have batted an eye

But I chose the opposite route, and if I can do it, so can you', "The purpose of money isn't to hoard it forever

Use it the way it was intended

Spend it to buy time and experiences

Spend it on things that bring you joy

And most importantly, spend it to create the world you want to see", "Money makes you more of who you already are

There is no other way', 'I‚Äôve taken two businesses to 7 and 8 figures in niches I knew NOTHING about.

And I used ONE skill to crush every business venture:

Sales.

If you can win the sale, everything else falls into place.

So here‚Äôs 5 tips to help you make the sale:', 'Before we start, I need to warn you: 

This is for long-game players ONLY. 

There's no "quick hack" to building a valuable network.

But if you start NOW, and you're willing to play the long game...

In 5 years, you'll never worry about money again. 

Let's get started...', "Two criminally underrated pieces of business advice:

1. Never stop selling

2. ALWAYS do what you say you're gonna do

What would you add?", 'The biggest mistake I see new entrepreneurs make is over-analyzing

You can spend 6 months getting everything "perfect"

Or you can spend 6 months moving as fast as possible and iterating your product/service according to market feedback

Which path will get you farther ahead?', "You'll learn more in 2 months of running your own business than you will in 4 years of business school", 'Don‚Äôt build a business to show how good you are 

Instead, build one to add the most value to society

Impossible to fail when you approach business with this mentality

Long term thinking > Short term thinking', '"Survival of the fittest" doesn't mean survival of the strongest

It means survival of the most ADAPTABLE

Your success is directly correlated to your ability to adapt

How do you adapt to feedback? To failures? To changing tastes and markets? To new technologies?

And do you‚Ä¶ https://t.co/1YVRDLiXTM', "Sunk cost fallacy has killed more entrepreneurs than I can count

Stop doubling down on things that aren't working

This includes products/employees/offers/clients

Invest in your winners and ruthlessly cut your losers", 'In the last 10 years, I‚Äôve:

> Quit my 9-5 job
> Lost millions
> Made tens of millions
> Became a dad

But NONE of it would‚Äôve been possible without my network. 

So here are 7 tips I‚Äôd give my younger self if I woke up tomorrow with 0 contacts:', 'Good afternoon to everyone except people who ask for discounts when their friends start a business', 'Being an entrepreneur is 40% problem solving, 40% leadership and 20% being your own therapist', 'Biggest trait I see in winners:

Ability to just figure things out

Stop waiting for someone to tell you how to do something

Stop waiting for someone to tell you what to do next

Stop asking  googleable questions

Employees wait around for instructions

Owners just go', "You'd be shocked at how many business owners I talk to don't measure the right numbers

There are usually 2-3 numbers that REALLY matter for your business

Everything else is just noise

Find the big levers, triple down on those, and stop worrying about the little stuff", 'A lot of big-name entrepreneurs talking about ditching work-life balance

"Who cares, work harder," they say

My philosophy:

You can have both. You can make big money AND be a great dad, for example.

You don't have to work harder. 

You have to work different. 

BIG distinction', "There's nothing wrong with having a little chip on your shoulder

The greatest men in history have all had something to prove

If you have to make up haters to get you motivated, do that

Just don't let it turn you into a bitter or cynical person

As with all things: balance", 'I went from quitting my 6 figure corporate job to losing $180,000 in my first business and facing bankruptcy‚Ä¶.

To building multiple businesses to 7 figures and beyond.

If you want to be a successful entrepreneur without an ivy league degree, read this:', "If you say negative things behind a person's back, they'll hear about it

If you say positive things behind a person's back, they'll hear about it

This is one of the most powerful pieces of networking advice I can give you", 'Just saw this today... feeling massive gratitude that my story is helping others

https://t.co/dns6ngX8Py', 'People love telling you to never be loyal to a company

"If you drop dead, your job will replace you tomorrow."

And a lot of times that's true

But be careful not to be shortsighted

There's a lot of power in proving your loyalty to valuable people

Don't burn golden bridges', "Big mistake young entrepreneurs make when they start doing well:

They start spending WAY above their level

Seen way too many guys buy a $30k watch then go belly up two months later

If you want to last, treat every deal like it's your last", "How to never worry about money again:

- Learn how to solve a problem people think about 24/7

- Learn how to sell

That's the whole list", 'Me in my 20s:

> Burned out from 9-5 job
> Almost went bankrupt
> Lost and confused

> Exited 2 businesses worth over 7 figs
> A dad
> Living with purpose

Here‚Äôs 5 steps I took to fulfil the American dream without handouts, Ivy league degrees or shortcuts:', 'Me in my 20s:

> Burned out from 9-5 job

> A dad

Here‚Äôs 5 steps I took to fulfil the American dream without handouts, Ivy league degrees or shortcuts:', "Ask any successful entrepreneur what their most valuable asset is and they'll all tell you the same thing:

Their reputation

It takes years to build and seconds to destroy. And it only gets more valuable the higher and more visible you become. Play long term games.", 'Losers think in days

Winners think in years

The are WRONG

I'm living proof that the American Dream is alive and well

what would you add?", "So much of business success is just showing up

1) never stop building your skills
2) never stop showing up 

Repeat, forever, and your success is guaranteed", "What I'm most proud of isn't the company I founded

If not, ask yourself why', 'Things that have shaped me:

> Mentored by a $100M entrepreneur in my early 20s
> Quitting the 9-5 to start my own business
> My friends and contacts

Instead, try to be the most useful and valuable person in the room. 

What you'll find is that everyone starts throwing their business card at you.

Impossible to lose when you do this.', '15 harsh business truths I learned going from an employee in Corporate America to breaking free as an entrepreneur living the American Dream: https://t.co/fpuD8LQ5f4', '"Being an entrepreneur isn't for everyone!"

BS

Before the industrial revolution, the majority of people were entrepreneurs

It's in your blood

You weren't born to serve your boss

You were born to serve your family

You were born to build

So start building', 'You've been lied to by the business gurus...

Turns out there's ZERO "self-made" success stories. 

Behind every top performer...is a great mentor. 

So here are the top 5 lessons from my billionaire mentor: 

(I've used these every day for 20 years)', "Originality is the most overrated principle in business.

My first 7 figure business was in construction. 

It was simple, boring but wildly profitable.

You'll get way farther doing what already works than trying to come up with something that's never been done before.", "What's one thing you wish you'd learned in school, but didn't?", '"Money can't buy happiness!"

Ok, that may be true...

But being broke doesn't buy it either', "Learning about business from a business school professor is like learning about battle from a World of Warcraft player

Learn from people who've been there before", 'When I became a dad I made a decision to work differently

I knew I had to put the days of 80 hour weeks behind me

Because at the end of the day only 3 things matter:

-How free you are
-How healthy you are
-How much your family loves you', "Me in my early 20s

- Wrecked my first business
- Owed $180k in damages
- Facing bankruptcy

Me in my 30s

- Built and scaled multiple businesses from scratch
- Living my dream

Here are 10 business lessons I'll be teaching my children:", 'I turned a $180,000 loss into a multi 7 figure business.
